War episodes

We assign an integer value 1-4 corresponding to the 4 respective war intervals explained in the report. A default value of 0 corresponds to a no war date.

In[]:
#set war label. 
#Default no war is zero. 
# Define the four specific date intervals
intervals = [(pd.to_datetime('2021-05-01'), pd.to_datetime('2021-05-30')),
             (pd.to_datetime('2022-08-01'), pd.to_datetime('2022-08-30')),
             (pd.to_datetime('2023-05-01'), pd.to_datetime('2023-05-30')),
             (pd.to_datetime('2023-10-07'), pd.to_datetime('2023-12-30'))]

# Initialize the 'condition' column with zeros (no war)
df['war'] = 0
# Assign integer values 1 to 4 based on the date intervals of the 4 respective war intervals
for i, interval in enumerate(intervals, start=1):
    df.loc[(df['date'] >= interval[0]) & (df['date'] < interval[1]), 'war'] = int(i)

# Groupby by WAR
war_df = df.groupby("war")

Preprocessing

In a political corpus, acronymns are essential in the analysis. Hence, special care is given to accronyms, which typically have low characters (e.g. USA, UN, WHO) Hence, only tokens with characters <1 are filtered out.

Punctuations and special characters are removed. Lower casing is applied only to words with >3 characters to retain the original casing of accronyms (for visualization purposes).

In[]:
#Preprocess
# Punctuations and Special Characters are removed
df['text'] = df['merged_text'].str.replace("[^a-zA-Z#]", " ")
df['text'] = df['text'].str.replace('[^\w\s]', '', regex=True)

#lower case only words with more than 3 chars, to keep accronyms upper case
df['text'] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(word.lower() if len(word) > 3 else word for word in x.split()))

Corpus specific stopwords extraction

A TF-IDF analysis of the text is conducted.

From its results, a list of relevant words are visually selected as an additional stopwords list to be filtered out from the text, going forward in our analysis.

In[]:
# Function to compute the TF-IDF of the ratings words, and extract the highest 50 for visual inspection.

def TFIDF_analysis(df,text):
    # Create a TfidfVectorizer, and remove standard english stopwords
    tfidf_vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words="english")

    # Fit and transform the 'Review' column
    tfidf_matrix = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(df[text])

    # Get feature names (words) from the TfidfVectorizer
    feature_names = tfidf_vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()

    # Calculate the mean TF-IDF scores for each word across all texts
    mean_tfidf_scores = tfidf_matrix.mean(axis=0).A1

    # Create a DataFrame with words and their mean TF-IDF scores
    tfidf_df = pd.DataFrame({'Word': feature_names, 'Mean_TFIDF': mean_tfidf_scores})

    # Sort the DataFrame by mean TF-IDF scores in descending order
    tfidf_df = tfidf_df.sort_values(by='Mean_TFIDF',ascending=False)

    # Extract the words with the lowest and highest TF-IDF scores
    lowest_tfidf_words = tfidf_df.tail(50)['Word'].to_list() 
    highest_tfidf_words = tfidf_df.head(50)['Word'].to_list() 
    return(tfidf_df)

tfidf_df= TFIDF_analysis(df,'text')

Wordcloud visualization

To track to the time evolution of language in our corpus, several wordclouds are created: overall data, the yearly evolution from 2021 to 2023, the four different war data, the 'no war' data.

In[]:
#Using standard NLT english stopwords 
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
stopwords.update(custom_stopwords)

# Function to plot wordcloud 
def plot_wordcloud(text,max_words):
    cloud = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800,
                background_color ='white',
                stopwords = stopwords,
                max_words=30,
                repeat=True,
                min_font_size = 10,
                normalize_plurals=True,
                min_word_length=1,
                collocations=False,
                random_state=2
                ).generate_from_text(text)
 
    plt.figure(figsize = (4, 4), facecolor = None)
    plt.imshow(cloud,interpolation="bilinear")
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout(pad = 0)
    plt.show()
    return()

Sentiment analysis: Extracting positive news

The purpose is to attempt to extract positive news among the corpus of news.

As the data is not labeled, this is an unsupervised learning exercise.

We attempt to classify the sentiment using pretrained models (open source), and assess the applicability and results for each model.

Two models pretrained models are used:

1/ Text Blob: trained on twitter posts.

2/ NLTK Vader: trained on reddit news headlines.

TextBlob

In[]:
#Determining the Polarity 
def sentiment_analyze(text):
    return TextBlob(text).sentiment.polarity

df['sentiment'] = df['stemmed_text'].apply(sentiment_analyze)

NLTK Vader pretrained

Textblob classified most entries in the neutral zone. The result is expected, as it was trained on twitter posts, rather than a news corpus.

We attempst NLTK vader package, guided by :https://www.learndatasci.com/tutorials/sentiment-analysis-reddit-headlines-pythons-nltk/

In[]:
sia = SIA()
results = []

# Predict polarity of each entry
for line in df['merged_text']:
    pol_score = sia.polarity_scores(line)
    pol_score['headline'] = line
    results.append(pol_score)

df_pol = pd.DataFrame.from_records(results)

NER: persons, organizations and countries

Named Entity Recognition is used to extract names of relevant parties involved in the conflict. SpaCY NER package is used.

In[]:
# NER: extract names of key players and stakeholders
NER=spacy.load("en_core_web_sm")

#keep only categories: persons, organizations, countries
ner_categories=['PERSON','GPE','ORG','NORP']
In[]:
# function to perform NER on a given text
def perform_ner(text):
    doc = NER(text)
    entities=[]
    labels=[]
    for ent in doc.ents:
        if ent.label_ in ner_categories:
            entities.append((ent.text)) 
            labels.append((ent.label_))
    return entities

# Apply the function to the 'stemmed_text' column of our DataFrame
df['entities'] = df['stemmed_text'].apply(perform_ner)

Time series analysis (aggregated over 1 month periods)

A TF-IDF analysis of the data for each period (1 month) is peformed.

The results are stored as a dictionary where each key corresponds to 1 period, and its value is the TF-IDF results dataframe.

In[]:
# Break the whole time range into 1 month periods
start_date = df['date'].min() - pd.DateOffset(months=1)
end_date = df['date'].max() + pd.DateOffset(months=1)
date_ranges = pd.date_range(start=start_date, end=end_date, freq='MS')

# Create a dictionary to store results for each month
results_dict = {}
# select words to track time evolution
select_words=NER_track

for i in range(len(date_ranges) - 1):
    start_date = date_ranges[i]
    end_date = date_ranges[i + 1]
    mask = (df['date'] >= start_date) & (df['date'] < end_date)
    monthly_dataframe = df.loc[mask].copy()

    # Compute TF-IDF results of the non-stemmed Tokens for each period
    tfidf_results = TFIDF_analysis(monthly_dataframe,'stemmed_text')
    tfidf_results['rank']= 0

    # Filter out words not in select_words
    if select_words is not None:
        tfidf_results = tfidf_results[tfidf_results['Word'].isin(select_words)].copy()

    # Add rank column of sorted terms    
    rank=tfidf_results.rank(method='first')
    tfidf_results['rank']= rank.iloc[:,2]
        
    results_dict[start_date] = tfidf_results[['Word','rank']]

#print(results_dict)
In[]:
# Merging all dataframes into 1 dataframe for comparison and visualization
merged_df = pd.DataFrame()

for date, df in results_dict.items():
    # Renaming the 'rank' column with the date
    df_time = df.rename(columns={'rank': date})
    
    # Merging dataframes
    if merged_df.empty:
        merged_df = df_time
    else:
        merged_df = pd.merge(merged_df, df_time, on='Word', how='outer')

# Function to plot the TF-IDF Rank vs time for each term from select list of words
def plot_time_series_word(unique_words):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))

    for word in unique_words:
        word_data = merged_df[merged_df['Word'] == word]
        plt.scatter(word_data.columns[1:], word_data.iloc[0, 1:], marker='o', label=word, s=300 )

    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('TF-IDF rank')
    plt.title('TF-IDF word Rank Over Time \n (Rank 1: most important)')
    plt.legend()
    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # defining the 4 war intervals
    date_intervals = [
    ('2021-05-01', '2021-05-30'),
    ('2022-08-01', '2022-08-30'),
    ('2023-05-01', '2023-05-30'),
    ('2023-10-07', '2023-12-31')]
    
    # Highlighting date intervals with vertical strips
    for start_date, end_date in date_intervals:
        plt.axvspan(pd.to_datetime(start_date), pd.to_datetime(end_date), alpha=0.2, color='blue')

    plt.show()

LCA

LCA is performed in an attempt to extract dominant themes in our data. The preprocessed stemmed text is used.

At first 2 components are investigated. Then 3 components results are shown.
